# Design quality — review contract

> The anti-slop contract the `implementer` builds to and the `design-reviewer` audits on any
> UI-touching diff (and `/design-audit` on demand). It sits **on top of** the mechanical gate and
> the Four R's: those judge code; this judges what the user sees. **Severity-driven** (Block /
> Advisory). A deterministic floor runs as `<%= it.verifyCmd %> --only design` — a static scan for the
> mechanically-detectable Slop tells (see below); the **depth** is the `design-reviewer`'s judgment,
> which this contract defines. The scan is a high-precision floor, **not** a substitute for it.

The goal is interfaces that look **intentional**, not generated. "AI slop" is the failure mode: a
templated look with no point of view — the same violet gradient, the same centered hero, the same
three icon-cards — that signals nobody decided anything. This contract names the decisions so the
implementer makes them and the reviewer can check them.

## Scope — when it applies

Triggers on any diff that touches **what renders**: components, pages, layouts, templates,
stylesheets, design tokens, CSS/Tailwind/utility classes, SVG/iconography, or copy shown in the UI.
Pure backend, build, or logic diffs are out of scope — route them to the normal review. If unsure
whether a change is user-visible, treat it as in scope.

## Implementer conditions — the pre-flight contract

Meet these **before** handing off any UI change. They come first because most slop is generated, not
designed — it is the default a model reaches for when it skips the context.

- **Brief inference first.** Before writing UI, read what already exists: the design tokens, theme,
  spacing/type scale, and the two or three closest existing components. Infer the brief from the
  product and the surrounding screens. Never invent a parallel look for one new screen.
- **Respect the design system — extend, don't overwrite.** Reuse the existing variables, primitives,
  and component library. A new color, font, radius, or shadow that isn't already in the system is a
  decision that needs a reason in the report — not a default.
- **Hard pre-flight check.** Before you hand off, walk the **Slop tells** list below and confirm the
  diff ships none of them. This is a gate on yourself, not a suggestion.
- **Dark-mode protocol.** If the project supports more than one theme, every new surface ships **all**
  supported themes. No hardcoded light-only colors; use the themed token.
- **Output completeness.** Ship the real thing: real copy (no Lorem, no "Card title"), and every
  state the surface can be in — **empty, loading, error**, and the populated/success state. A screen
  that only renders the happy path with placeholder data is not done.
- **Accessibility is part of done**, not a later pass — see the Accessibility discipline.
<% if (it.isSdd) { %>- **Build to the spec.** "In-contract" UX (states, copy, flows) comes from the approved
  `specs/<feature>/` — implement what it says, no more.
<% } %>
## Disciplines

Each discipline lists the **implementer conditions** (the bar) and the **reviewer checks** (how it is
verified), then a severity note. The disciplines are deliberately narrow so findings don't overlap.

### Typography — hierarchy through scale and weight, not noise

- **Implementer:** establish hierarchy with a small type scale and weight, not arbitrary pixel sizes;
  cap at ~2 families (one for UI, optionally one for display); keep body line-length readable
  (~45–75ch) and line-height generous; align to the existing scale.
- **Reviewer:** headings that differ from body by a hair instead of a clear step; more than two
  families or a decorative font used for body; one-off `font-size` values off the scale; cramped
  line-height on long text.
- **Severity:** Block when hierarchy is unreadable (everything looks the same weight/size). Advisory
  for minor scale drift.

### Color — inherit the palette; contrast carries meaning

- **Implementer:** use the project's palette tokens; pick colors for **contrast and meaning**, not
  decoration; reserve a single accent and use it sparingly; never convey state by hue alone.
- **Reviewer:** raw hex/`rgb()` literals instead of tokens; a second or third accent competing for
  attention; the generic AI palette (see Slop tells); low-contrast text.
- **Severity:** Block on the generic-palette tell or text that fails contrast. Advisory for a stray
  literal that matches an existing token.

### Layout & spacing — alignment and rhythm on a scale

- **Implementer:** lay out on the existing spacing scale; align elements to a grid; use whitespace
  deliberately to group and separate; match the layout to the surface (an app dashboard is not a
  marketing page).
- **Reviewer:** arbitrary pixel margins/paddings off the scale; misaligned edges; a reading-column
  (`max-w-prose`, centered) layout applied to dense app UI; uniform spacing with no grouping.
- **Severity:** Block when spacing is visibly arbitrary/inconsistent across a surface. Advisory for a
  single off-scale value.

### Components — reuse primitives; every state designed

- **Implementer:** compose from existing primitives before building new ones; give every interactive
  element its full set of states — **default, hover, focus-visible, active, disabled** (and selected
  where it applies); keep one component one responsibility.
- **Reviewer:** a bespoke one-off that duplicates an existing primitive; a button/input missing hover
  or focus states; inconsistent variants of the "same" component across screens.
- **Severity:** Block on a missing focus-visible state (also an a11y block) or a reinvented core
  primitive. Advisory for a missing hover polish.

### Accessibility — usable by everyone, by default

- **Implementer:** semantic elements (`button`, `nav`, `label`) over `div` soup; visible
  `focus-visible` on every interactive element; keyboard-operable; alt text on meaningful images and
  labels on icon-only controls; pointer targets ≥ 24px; meaning never by color alone; respect
  `prefers-reduced-motion` (see `docs/motion.md`).
- **Reviewer:** clickable `div`s with no role/keyboard handling; no focus indicator; icon buttons with
  no accessible name; low contrast; tiny targets.
- **Severity:** Block on no-keyboard-access or no accessible name for a control. Advisory for a
  borderline target size.

### Content & voice — concrete copy in the product's voice

- **Implementer:** write microcopy that is specific and in the product's voice; label buttons with
  the action ("Create project", not "Submit"); make empty and error states helpful and human; if a
  `DESIGN.md`/`PRODUCT.md` defines voice or anti-references, follow it.
- **Reviewer:** generic filler ("Welcome to your dashboard!"), vague CTAs ("Click here", "Submit"),
  empty states that just say "No data", error messages that leak internals or blame the user.
- **Severity:** Block on placeholder/Lorem copy shipped to a user-visible surface. Advisory for a weak
  but functional line.

## Slop tells — never ship these

These are the reflexive AI defaults that make an interface read as generated. Any one of them in a
UI diff is a **Block on sight** unless there is an explicit, documented design reason.

1. **Gradient text** on headings (rainbow / violet-to-pink `background-clip: text`).
2. **Side-stripe / left-accent borders** — the 3–4px colored bar down the side of a card.
3. **The generic AI palette** — indigo/violet → cyan as the brand color "because it looks techy".
4. **Oversized centered hero** — giant centered headline + subtitle + two pill buttons, all centered,
   on a surface that isn't a landing page.
5. **Emoji as UI icons** — sparkles/rocket/lightbulb standing in for a real icon set in app chrome.
6. **Glassmorphism by default** — frosted `backdrop-blur` cards with no reason to be translucent.
7. **Uniform `rounded-2xl` + drop-shadow on everything** — every element same radius, same float.
8. **Pill buttons with gradient fills** and no real hover/focus/disabled differentiation.
9. **Three evenly-spaced "feature cards"** — icon-in-a-rounded-square + title + one sentence, ×3.
10. **Unmotivated full-bleed gradient** section backgrounds.
11. **Decorative blurred gradient blobs** floating behind content.
12. **Low-contrast gray-on-gray** body text (e.g. light gray on white).
13. **Arbitrary spacing** — hand-picked pixel values instead of the spacing scale.
14. **Hover-scale on everything** (`scale-105` on cards, buttons, and images alike).
15. **Placeholder content shipped** — Lorem ipsum, "Card Title", gray rectangle "images".
16. **Centered reading-column app UI** — `max-w-prose mx-auto` wrapped around a dashboard.

### What the deterministic scan catches

`<%= it.verifyCmd %> --only design` is a regex floor over UI files (`.css`, `.scss`, `.tsx`, `.jsx`,
`.vue`, `.svelte`, `.astro`, `.html`, `.mdx`). It catches the mechanically-detectable tells only:

- **Block** (fail the gate at the default `failOn: "block"`): placeholder content (`Lorem ipsum`),
  gradient text (`bg-clip-text` + `text-transparent`).
- **Advisory** (reported, do not fail by default): the generic indigo/violet→pink/cyan gradient
  palette, default glassmorphism (`backdrop-blur` on a translucent surface), `hover:scale-*` on many
  elements, and arbitrary off-scale `[…px]` spacing.

Everything else on this list — hierarchy, contrast, the centered hero, three-card layouts, emoji
icons, design-system fidelity — is **not** mechanically checkable and is the `design-reviewer`'s job.
Tune the scan in `reins.config.json` → `design.slopScan` (`enabled`, `failOn`).

## Severity guide

- **Block** — any Slop tell present; broken/unreadable hierarchy; the design system overridden with
  unjustified new tokens; a supported theme or a required state (empty/loading/error) missing on a
  shipped surface; a keyboard/focus/contrast a11y failure; placeholder copy on a user-visible screen.
- **Advisory** — minor scale or spacing drift, a single off-token literal that matches an existing
  value, a weak-but-working microcopy line, a hover polish left undone.

A **Block**-severity finding warrants `DESIGN_BLOCK` (the design-reviewer's `CHANGES_REQUESTED`).
Advisory findings are recorded but do not block.

## Optional inputs — DESIGN.md / PRODUCT.md

If the project carries a `DESIGN.md` (tokens, components, brand rules) or a `PRODUCT.md` (users,
voice, anti-references), read it **first** — it overrides defaults and resolves taste questions this
contract leaves open. Brand surfaces (marketing) and product surfaces (the app) follow different
rules; when both exist, treat the named one as authoritative for that surface.
